window.MSK_SHOULDER = [
  {
    id: 'rotator-cuff-tendinopathy',
    name: 'Rotator Cuff Tendinopathy',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Rotator cuff tendinopathy</strong> is a degenerative condition of the rotator cuff tendons — most commonly the supraspinatus — characterised by failed healing response, collagen disorganisation, and neovascularisation within the tendon substance. It is the most prevalent shoulder condition in clinical practice, accounting for approximately 70% of shoulder pain presentations.</p><p>The term "tendinopathy" encompasses both <em>tendinosis</em> (intrinsic degenerative change without inflammation) and <em>reactive tendinopathy</em> (early load-reactive change). The Cook & Purdam continuum model (2009) provides the dominant conceptual framework: reactive → tendon disrepair → degenerative tendinopathy.</p>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p>The rotator cuff comprises four muscles arising from the scapula and inserting onto the humeral head:</p><ul><li><strong>Supraspinatus</strong> — superior fossa → greater tuberosity (superior facet); primary abductor; most commonly affected (critical zone of relative avascularity 1 cm proximal to insertion)</li><li><strong>Infraspinatus</strong> — infraspinous fossa → greater tuberosity (middle facet); primary external rotator</li><li><strong>Teres minor</strong> — lateral scapula border → greater tuberosity (inferior facet); external rotation/adduction</li><li><strong>Subscapularis</strong> — subscapular fossa → lesser tuberosity; primary internal rotator</li></ul><p>The <strong>subacromial space</strong> (7–14 mm normally) contains the supraspinatus tendon, subacromial bursa, and long head biceps tendon. The coracoacromial arch (acromion, coracoacromial ligament, coracoid) forms the superior boundary. Acromial morphology (Bigliani Type II hooked, Type III curved) reduces space and predisposes to mechanical impingement.</p>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p>The critical zone of the supraspinatus (1 cm proximal to insertion) has relatively poor vascularity, particularly with arm in dependent position. Under repetitive mechanical load, the normal tendon repair response is overwhelmed. Key histopathological findings:</p><ul><li>Collagen fibre disorganisation (parallel type I → disorganised type III)</li><li>Increased ground substance and proteoglycan accumulation</li><li>Neovascularisation (angiogenesis correlated with pain via CGRP/substance P)</li><li>Tenocyte apoptosis and failed healing</li><li>Absence of inflammatory infiltrate in established tendinopathy</li></ul><p>Compressive load at the tendon enthesis (particularly in positions >60° abduction) accelerates degeneration. Internal impingement of the posterior-superior cuff against the glenoid rim occurs in overhead athletes.</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Occupational overhead loading (&gt;60° elevation &gt;2 hours/day)</li><li>Repetitive reaching tasks</li><li>Scapular dyskinesis and poor neuromuscular control</li><li>Poor posture (thoracic kyphosis, forward head posture)</li><li>Sudden increase in training load (runners transitioning to overhead sports)</li><li>Smoking (impairs tendon vascularity)</li><li>Obesity (increased systemic tendinopathy risk)</li><li>Fluoroquinolone antibiotic use</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Age &gt;40 years (prevalence increases markedly)</li><li>Type II or III acromial morphology</li><li>OS acromiale</li><li>Glenohumeral anatomical variants</li><li>Family history / genetic tendon collagen variants</li><li>Diabetes mellitus (associated with greater tendon degeneration)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Aching pain localised to lateral deltoid region and anterior shoulder. Pain aggravated by overhead activities, reaching behind back, sleeping on affected side. Often insidious onset.</p><p><strong>Signs:</strong></p><ul><li>Painful arc of abduction: 60–120° (classic supraspinatus impingement zone)</li><li>Pain on resisted abduction and external rotation</li><li>Tenderness over the greater tuberosity / supraspinatus insertion</li><li>Possible reduced ROM in forward flexion and internal rotation (differentiate from adhesive capsulitis)</li></ul><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th><th>What it detects</th></tr><tr><td>Hawkins-Kennedy</td><td>79%</td><td>59%</td><td>Subacromial impingement</td></tr><tr><td>Neer's Sign</td><td>72%</td><td>60%</td><td>Subacromial impingement</td></tr><tr><td>Empty Can (Jobe)</td><td>69%</td><td>66%</td><td>Supraspinatus integrity/pain</td></tr><tr><td>Full Can</td><td>66%</td><td>64%</td><td>Supraspinatus strength</td></tr><tr><td>External Rotation Lag Sign</td><td>70%</td><td>100%</td><td>Infraspinatus/teres minor tear</td></tr><tr><td>Lift-off Test (Gerber)</td><td>62%</td><td>100%</td><td>Subscapularis tear</td></tr></table>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<h4>Validated Outcome Measures</h4><ul><li><strong>DASH (Disabilities of the Arm, Shoulder and Hand)</strong> — 30-item PRO; MDC 10.8 points; MCID 10–15 points. Gold standard for upper limb function.</li><li><strong>WORC (Western Ontario Rotator Cuff Index)</strong> — 21-item disease-specific PRO; MCID 11% change from baseline.</li><li><strong>NPRS (Numeric Pain Rating Scale, 0–10)</strong> — MDC 2 points; MCID 2 points. Use for pain at rest and with activity.</li><li><strong>PSFS (Patient-Specific Functional Scale)</strong> — patient-nominated activities; MCID 2–3 points; highly responsive to change.</li><li><strong>ASES (American Shoulder and Elbow Surgeons Score)</strong> — MCID 12–17 points.</li></ul><h4>Physical Assessment</h4><ul><li>Shoulder ROM goniometry (forward flexion, abduction, IR/ER at 0° and 90°)</li><li>Scapular upward rotation assessment (inclinometer)</li><li>Isometric strength testing — dynamometry preferred (ER/IR ratio; &lt;0.75 ER:IR = deficit)</li><li>Cervical screen (C5-C6 dermatomal distribution)</li><li>Thoracic mobility assessment</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<p><strong>Imaging is not required for initial management</strong> in uncomplicated tendinopathy. NICE guidelines recommend conservative management trial of 6 weeks before imaging.</p><ul><li><strong>Ultrasound (USS)</strong> — first-line; dynamic assessment of subacromial space, tendon integrity, and bursal thickening. Sensitivity 87%, specificity 96% for partial thickness tears. Doppler can demonstrate neovascularisation.</li><li><strong>MRI</strong> — gold standard for full characterisation; demonstrates tendon signal change, partial/full tears, muscle atrophy, and bone pathology. T2 hyperintensity = fluid/tear; intermediate signal = degeneration.</li><li><strong>X-ray</strong> — limited value; assess for calcific deposits (AP and outlet views), acromial morphology, glenohumeral arthritis. Subacromial space &lt;6 mm = significant.</li><li><strong>MRI arthrogram</strong> — superior sensitivity for partial articular surface tears (PASTA lesions).</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Rotator cuff tear (partial or full thickness)</li><li>Subacromial bursitis</li><li>Calcific tendinitis</li><li>Adhesive capsulitis (reduced passive ROM distinguishes)</li><li>Acromioclavicular joint pathology (horizontal adduction test positive)</li><li>Glenohumeral osteoarthritis</li><li>SLAP lesion (Speed's test, O'Brien's test)</li><li>Cervical radiculopathy C5 (dermatomal distribution, cervical provocation positive)</li><li>Referred pain from cardiac (especially left shoulder — urgent)</li><li>Shoulder impingement secondary to lung apex lesion (Pancoast tumour — check for Horner's syndrome)</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<p><strong>The following findings warrant urgent medical referral:</strong></p><ul><li>Constant, unremitting pain unresponsive to position changes (consider bone pathology/malignancy)</li><li>Bilateral shoulder pain with systemic features (PMR — ESR >40, age >50)</li><li>Night sweats, unexplained weight loss, fever (malignancy)</li><li>Horner's syndrome with shoulder/arm pain (Pancoast tumour)</li><li>Rapid onset profound weakness/wasting without preceding pain (neuralgic amyotrophy/Parsonage-Turner)</li><li>Shoulder pain with left-sided radiation, chest tightness, dyspnoea (cardiac referral)</li><li>History of cancer with new shoulder pain</li><li>Shoulder pain in child/adolescent (&lt;16 years) — consider physeal injury or bone tumour</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute / Reactive Phase (0–6 weeks)</div><ul><li><strong>Load management:</strong> Identify and modify provocative activities; avoid full elimination (disuse worsens tendinopathy)</li><li><strong>Isometric exercises:</strong> 5 × 45-second holds, moderate intensity (≥70% MVC), daily — analgesic effect (Rio et al., 2015); wall press, isometric ER/IR</li><li><strong>Education:</strong> Explain tendon continuum model; reassure about prognosis; avoid aggravating postures</li><li><strong>Modalities:</strong> Ice/heat for symptom relief (adjunct only); LLLT may reduce pain (Cochrane 2013)</li><li><strong>Corticosteroid injection:</strong> NICE-recommended for short-term pain relief if conservative fails at 6 weeks (limit 1–2; evidence of tendon weakening with repeated injections)</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute Phase (6–12 weeks)</div><ul><li><strong>Progressive isotonic loading:</strong> Begin slow eccentrics (3-second lowering phase), progress to eccentric-concentric; FITT: 3 sets × 12–15 reps, 3×/week, moderate load (6–7/10 pain acceptable)</li><li><strong>Scapular stabilisation:</strong> Lower trapezius (prone Y/T), serratus anterior (wall slides, push-up plus)</li><li><strong>Postural retraining:</strong> Thoracic extension exercises, pectoralis minor stretching</li><li><strong>Neural mobilisation:</strong> If contributing cervical component</li><li><strong>Exercise prescription (FITT):</strong> F — 3×/week; I — 6–7/10 pain during, &lt;24h post; T — 15–20 min; T — isotonic progressive resistance</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Chronic/Return-to-Activity Phase (12+ weeks)</div><ul><li><strong>Heavy Slow Resistance (HSR):</strong> Kongsgaard et al. (2009/2010) — equal efficacy to eccentric-only; 6-rep max loads, 3 sets, slow cadence (3-0-3); superior tendon collagen remodelling</li><li><strong>Functional progressions:</strong> Sport-/occupation-specific loading, overhead press, throwing progressions</li><li><strong>Plyometric loading:</strong> Medicine ball throws, wall catches</li><li><strong>Return-to-sport criteria:</strong> Symmetrical strength (ER:IR ≥0.75), pain-free sport-specific movement, DASH ≤10</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<p>Prognosis is generally favourable with appropriate conservative management:</p><ul><li>60–90% of patients respond to conservative treatment within 3–6 months</li><li>Recurrence rate is high (~40%) if underlying load management and kinetic chain deficits not addressed</li><li>Negative prognostic factors: psychological distress, high baseline pain, bilateral involvement, previous injection</li><li>Surgery (subacromial decompression) is not superior to physiotherapy (CSAW trial, Beard et al., 2018, NEJM — sham surgery equivalent)</li><li>Tendinopathy without associated tear: excellent prognosis with exercise</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>NICE NG248 (2023):</strong> Exercise therapy first-line; corticosteroid injection for short-term pain if exercise alone insufficient; surgery not routinely recommended</li><li><strong>Cochrane Review (Page et al., 2016):</strong> Exercise superior to placebo for pain and function; manual therapy adds modest benefit as adjunct</li><li><strong>Kongsgaard et al. (2010):</strong> HSR loading equivalent to eccentric-only for supraspinatus; both superior to corticosteroid injection at 12 months</li><li><strong>CSAW Trial (Beard et al., 2018, NEJM):</strong> Subacromial decompression surgery not superior to sham surgery or physiotherapy-alone — landmark trial supporting conservative management</li><li><strong>Rio et al. (2015, BJSM):</strong> Isometric exercise produces immediate cortical pain inhibition superior to isotonic exercise in reactive tendinopathy</li><li><strong>Cook & Purdam continuum model (2009, BJSM):</strong> Foundational framework for tendinopathy classification and management</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'rotator-cuff-tear',
    name: 'Rotator Cuff Tear (Full Thickness)',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p>A <strong>full-thickness rotator cuff tear (FTRCT)</strong> is a complete disruption through the entire thickness of the tendon from articular to bursal surface, classified by size: small (&lt;1 cm), medium (1–3 cm), large (3–5 cm), and massive (&gt;5 cm or ≥2 tendons). Supraspinatus is most commonly affected. Prevalence increases markedly with age: 4% at age 40, rising to 50% at age 80. Asymptomatic tears are common (~50% of all full-thickness tears).</p><p>Mechanism: <em>Traumatic</em> (fall on outstretched hand, forced abduction) or <em>degenerative</em> (progressive tendon failure on background of tendinopathy). Traumatic tears in younger patients (&lt;40 years) warrant early surgical consideration.</p>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p>The supraspinatus footprint on the greater tuberosity measures ~12 mm × 23 mm. Full-thickness tears typically initiate at the anterior margin of the supraspinatus ("crescent-shaped" zone) and propagate posteriorly to involve infraspinatus, and anteriorly into subscapularis (massive tear pattern).</p><p><strong>Tear classification systems:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Bateman classification:</strong> Grade I–IV based on retraction</li><li><strong>DeOrio & Cofield:</strong> Small/medium/large/massive (most clinically used)</li><li><strong>Lafosse:</strong> Subscapularis involvement (I–V)</li></ul><p>Chronic tears develop <strong>fatty infiltration</strong> (Goutallier Grade 0–4) and muscle atrophy — both are key prognostic indicators for surgical outcome and irreversibility.</p>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p>Full-thickness tears allow subacromial and glenohumeral fluid communication. Tear propagation is driven by cyclic mechanical loading on the tear margin. Chronic tears develop:</p><ul><li>Muscle retraction and shortening</li><li>Fatty infiltration (Goutallier Grade ≥2 = poor surgical prognosis)</li><li>Superior humeral head migration (loss of supraspinatus depressor function → coracohumeral arch impingement)</li><li>Secondary glenohumeral arthritis (cuff tear arthropathy — Hamada classification)</li></ul><p>The deltoid-rotator cuff force couple is disrupted. Remaining cuff muscles (particularly subscapularis and lower infraspinatus) attempt compensation. Physical therapy targeting these compensators forms the basis of conservative management.</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Untreated rotator cuff tendinopathy</li><li>Repetitive overhead loading</li><li>Smoking (RR 2.0 — impairs tendon healing)</li><li>Corticosteroid injection history (repeated injection weakens tendon)</li><li>High-load occupational exposure</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Age (strongest predictor — prevalence 30% at 60 years)</li><li>Male sex</li><li>Dominant arm</li><li>Type III hooked acromion</li><li>Contralateral cuff tear (50% bilateral within 5 years)</li><li>Diabetes mellitus</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Shoulder pain (lateral deltoid), weakness, and functional limitation. Night pain (inability to sleep on affected side) is prominent. Traumatic tears: sudden pain + audible pop + acute weakness. Degenerative: insidious progressive weakness.</p><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th><th>Target</th></tr><tr><td>Drop Arm Test</td><td>21%</td><td>92%</td><td>Large/massive tears</td></tr><tr><td>Empty Can (Jobe)</td><td>69%</td><td>66%</td><td>Supraspinatus</td></tr><tr><td>External Rotation Lag Sign</td><td>70%</td><td>100%</td><td>Infraspinatus tear</td></tr><tr><td>Hornblower's Sign</td><td>100%</td><td>93%</td><td>Teres minor tear (massive)</td></tr><tr><td>Lift-off (Gerber)</td><td>62%</td><td>100%</td><td>Subscapularis tear</td></tr><tr><td>Bear-Hug Test</td><td>60%</td><td>92%</td><td>Subscapularis (upper)</td></tr><tr><td>Belly-Press Test</td><td>40%</td><td>98%</td><td>Subscapularis (lower)</td></tr></table>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>WORC (Western Ontario Rotator Cuff Index)</strong> — disease-specific; MCID 11%; most sensitive for cuff tears</li><li><strong>ASES (American Shoulder and Elbow Surgeons)</strong> — MCID 12–17 points; validated for surgical outcomes</li><li><strong>Oxford Shoulder Score</strong> — MCID 8 points; validated for surgical outcomes in NHS setting</li><li><strong>DASH</strong> — MCID 10–15 points; broad upper limb function</li><li><strong>Constant-Murley Score</strong> — objective + subjective; widely used in surgical literature</li><li><strong>Shoulder Strength Testing:</strong> Hand-held dynamometry ER/IR/abduction; ER:IR ratio target ≥0.75</li><li><strong>Functional reach / single-arm carry tests</strong></li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>MRI (non-contrast)</strong> — gold standard; determines tear size, retraction, muscle atrophy, and fatty infiltration (Goutallier grading). T2 bright signal = full thickness discontinuity. Sensitivity 92%, specificity 93%.</li><li><strong>Ultrasound</strong> — dynamic; operator-dependent; sensitivity 87%, specificity 94% for FTRCT; allows contralateral comparison</li><li><strong>X-ray</strong> — AP, outlet, and axillary views; superior humeral migration (≤7 mm acromiohumeral interval = massive tear); assess for calcification and arthritis</li><li><strong>MRI arthrogram</strong> — superior for partial vs full distinction; demonstrates contrast leak from joint to bursal space in FTRCT</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Rotator cuff tendinopathy (without structural tear)</li><li>Subacromial bursitis</li><li>Adhesive capsulitis</li><li>Glenohumeral instability</li><li>Acromioclavicular joint injury</li><li>Biceps tendon pathology (SLAP lesion, biceps tendinopathy)</li><li>Cervical radiculopathy (C5–C6)</li><li>Neuralgic amyotrophy (Parsonage-Turner syndrome) — profound rapid wasting without significant shoulder pathology</li><li>Glenohumeral osteoarthritis</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Traumatic tear in a patient &lt;40 years — early surgical assessment recommended (Cook & Maffulli, 2015)</li><li>Acute traumatic tear with dislocation — concurrent Hill-Sachs/bony Bankart likely; urgent orthopaedic review</li><li>Rapid progressive weakness without significant pain (Parsonage-Turner — urgent neurology referral)</li><li>Cervical myelopathy signs (bilateral upper limb weakness, lower limb spasticity, Hoffmann sign)</li><li>Night pain + weight loss + age &gt;50 — rule out metastatic disease</li><li>Progressive superior migration on serial X-rays — evolving cuff tear arthropathy, refer to orthopaedics</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute Phase (0–6 weeks) — Conservative</div><ul><li>Sling use for comfort in first 1–2 weeks (avoid prolonged immobilisation)</li><li>Pain management: NSAIDs (short-term), ice/heat</li><li>Pendulum exercises and passive/active-assisted ROM</li><li>Isometric contractions: deltoid, biceps, IR/ER</li><li>Patient education: tear characteristics, conservative vs surgical decision framework</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute Phase (6–12 weeks)</div><ul><li>Active ROM restoration: especially ER and forward flexion</li><li>Rotator cuff activation: side-lying ER, sidelying prone ER, scaption</li><li>Scapular stabilisation: low-load serratus anterior (wall slides), lower trapezius (prone Y)</li><li>Progressive resistance: theraband ER/IR, shoulder press if tolerated</li><li>Aquatic therapy as adjunct for large tears</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Chronic Phase / Ongoing Conservative</div><ul><li>Strengthening focus: deltoid, infraspinatus, subscapularis (preserving function of intact cuff)</li><li>Kinetic chain integration: hip/core stability, scapulo-thoracic exercises</li><li>Heavy Slow Resistance (Kongsgaard protocol) for residual tendinopathic tissue</li><li><strong>Surgical pathway:</strong> Refer if: failure of 3–6 months conservative management; traumatic tear &lt;40 years; large/massive tear with functional limitation; progressive muscle atrophy (Goutallier ≥2)</li><li><strong>Post-surgical rehabilitation:</strong> Phase 1 (0–6 weeks): sling/passive ROM; Phase 2 (6–12 weeks): active ROM + isometrics; Phase 3 (3–6 months): strengthening; Phase 4 (6–12 months): return to sport</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<p>Conservative management is effective in many patients, even with full-thickness tears:</p><ul><li>Ainsworth et al. (2009): 73% satisfaction with conservative management at 22 months for small/medium tears</li><li>Tear size progression: ~50% of conservatively managed tears progress in size over 2–5 years</li><li>Surgical outcomes (arthroscopic repair): &gt;85% satisfaction; re-tear rate 20–30% (higher with large tears, poor tissue quality)</li><li>Goutallier Grade ≥2 = poor surgical prognosis (irreversible fatty infiltration)</li><li>Massive irreparable tears: reverse total shoulder arthroplasty (rTSA) offers excellent outcomes in elderly patients</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Kukkonen et al. (2015, JBJS):</strong> RCT — no significant difference between physiotherapy, acromioplasty, and cuff repair for small/medium tears at 2 years</li><li><strong>Moosmayer et al. (2019, JBJS):</strong> 10-year follow-up RCT — surgical repair superior to physiotherapy for medium-large tears at 10 years (function and integrity)</li><li><strong>CSAW Trial (Beard et al., 2018):</strong> Subacromial decompression no better than sham or physiotherapy; does not apply directly to full-thickness tears</li><li><strong>NICE NG248 (2023):</strong> Physiotherapy first-line; surgery for failed conservative management or acute traumatic large tears</li><li><strong>Cochrane Review (Saltychev et al., 2015):</strong> Insufficient high-quality RCTs to definitively favour surgery over conservative treatment for degenerative tears</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'subacromial-impingement',
    name: 'Subacromial Impingement Syndrome',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Subacromial Impingement Syndrome (SIS)</strong> — now more accurately termed <em>subacromial pain syndrome (SAPS)</em> per the ISAKOS consensus — describes mechanical compression of subacromial structures (bursa, supraspinatus tendon, biceps long head) beneath the coracoacromial arch. It is a clinical diagnosis accounting for 44–65% of all shoulder pain presentations.</p><p>The terminology debate reflects evolving understanding: "impingement" implies purely structural/mechanical compression, whereas modern evidence suggests neuromuscular, psychosocial, and systemic sensitisation factors contribute substantially. The CSAW trial (2018) challenged the mechanical model by showing sham surgery = decompression surgery = physiotherapy.</p>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p>The subacromial space (normal: 9–10 mm on plain X-ray) is bounded superiorly by the coracoacromial arch (acromion, CA ligament, coracoid process) and inferiorly by the humeral head. Contents: supraspinatus tendon, subacromial/subdeltoid bursa, long head of biceps tendon at rotator interval.</p><p><strong>Acromial morphology (Bigliani classification):</strong></p><ul><li>Type I: flat (least impingement risk)</li><li>Type II: curved (moderate risk)</li><li>Type III: hooked (highest mechanical compression risk)</li><li>Type IV: convex</li></ul><p>Dynamic narrowing occurs during arm elevation and internal rotation. Pathological scapular kinematics (reduced upward rotation, posterior tipping) dynamically reduce subacromial space.</p>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p>Two mechanisms are proposed:</p><p><strong>Primary (structural):</strong> Acromial morphology, osteophytes, os acromiale, or thickened CA ligament reduce space and directly compress cuff.</p><p><strong>Secondary (functional):</strong> Scapular dyskinesis, rotator cuff weakness/fatigue, and glenohumeral instability result in superior humeral head migration and dynamic space reduction. This is the predominant mechanism in younger athletes and is most amenable to physiotherapy.</p><p>The subacromial bursa acts as a hydraulic shock absorber; repeated compression causes bursal thickening, inflammation, and painful fibrosis. Nociceptive sensitisation (central and peripheral) contributes to ongoing pain independent of structural compression.</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Overhead occupational exposure (painters, plasterers)</li><li>Rotator cuff weakness and imbalance</li><li>Scapular dyskinesis</li><li>Thoracic hyperkyphosis / poor posture</li><li>Pectoralis minor tightness</li><li>Sudden increase in overhead training volume</li><li>Technique errors in overhead sport</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Type II/III acromion</li><li>Os acromiale</li><li>Age (degenerative changes)</li><li>Glenohumeral anatomical variants</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Lateral shoulder pain, painful arc (60–120° abduction), pain reaching overhead or behind back, night pain, weakness.</p><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th></tr><tr><td>Hawkins-Kennedy</td><td>79%</td><td>59%</td></tr><tr><td>Neer's sign</td><td>72%</td><td>60%</td></tr><tr><td>Painful arc (60–120°)</td><td>74%</td><td>81%</td></tr><tr><td>Neer's test (injection)</td><td>88%</td><td>—</td></tr></table><p><strong>Scapular dyskinesis assessment:</strong> Lateral scapular slide test, dynamic kinematics during arm elevation (winging, anterior tilting, asymmetry). Kibler classification (Type I: inferior angle; Type II: medial border; Type III: superior border).</p>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>DASH</strong> — MCID 10–15 points</li><li><strong>WORC</strong> — disease-specific for cuff pathology; MCID 11%</li><li><strong>NPRS</strong> — 0–10; MCID 2 points</li><li><strong>PSFS</strong> — 3 patient-specific activities; MCID 2–3 points</li><li><strong>Shoulder Pain and Disability Index (SPADI)</strong> — 13-item; MCID 8–13 points; widely used in research</li><li><strong>Scapular dyskinesis assessment:</strong> lateral scapular slide test (≥1.5 cm asymmetry = clinically significant)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>X-ray:</strong> AP, outlet, and axillary views. Measure acromiohumeral interval (normal ≥7 mm). Identify acromial morphology, calcification, OA changes.</li><li><strong>USS:</strong> Dynamic assessment; bursal thickening (&gt;2 mm = abnormal), tendon integrity, CA ligament calcification</li><li><strong>MRI:</strong> Characterises subacromial bursal oedema, tendon signal change, and rules out complete tear. Not routinely required in primary care.</li></ul><p><em>Note: Imaging findings correlate poorly with symptoms — asymptomatic structural abnormalities are extremely common; treat the patient, not the scan.</em></p>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Rotator cuff tendinopathy (overlap significant)</li><li>Rotator cuff tear</li><li>Adhesive capsulitis (restricted passive ROM)</li><li>AC joint pathology</li><li>Bicipital tendinopathy</li><li>Cervical radiculopathy C5</li><li>Glenohumeral instability</li><li>SLAP lesion</li><li>Calcific tendinitis (acute intense pain)</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Bilateral shoulder girdle pain with morning stiffness &gt;45 min, elevated ESR/CRP, age &gt;50 — <strong>Polymyalgia Rheumatica</strong>: urgent GP/rheumatology</li><li>Constant unremitting pain, night sweats, weight loss — malignancy</li><li>History of breast, lung, or prostate cancer with shoulder pain — metastatic disease</li><li>Rapidly progressive weakness/atrophy (Parsonage-Turner)</li><li>Horner's syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis) with shoulder pain — Pancoast tumour</li><li>Diaphragmatic irritation referred to shoulder tip — hepatic/splenic pathology (urgent)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute Phase (0–6 weeks)</div><ul><li>Activity modification: avoid provocative overhead tasks; maintain below-shoulder activities</li><li>Pain relief: NSAIDs, ice, TENS (adjunct)</li><li>Corticosteroid injection: recommended by NICE for short-term pain control if limiting function</li><li>Pendulum exercises, active-assisted ROM, cervical/thoracic mobilisation</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute Phase (6–12 weeks)</div><ul><li><strong>Scapular stabilisation programme:</strong> Key focus<br>— Lower trapezius: prone Y/T/W with 2–3 kg (3×12)<br>— Serratus anterior: wall slides, push-up plus, dynamic hug<br>— Mid-trapezius: prone rows</li><li><strong>Rotator cuff strengthening:</strong> ER (side-lying, 30° abduction), IR, full can in scaption, sidelying abduction to 90°</li><li><strong>Thoracic mobilisation:</strong> Thoracic extension over foam roller, thoracic manipulation (evidence for improved shoulder kinematics — Boyles et al., 2009)</li><li>Pectoralis minor stretching (corner stretch)</li><li>Glenohumeral posterior capsule stretch (sleeper stretch)</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Chronic Phase (12+ weeks)</div><ul><li>Progressive overhead loading programme (controlled)</li><li>Kinetic chain integration: core stability, hip strengthening, rotational power</li><li>Sport/occupation-specific training</li><li><strong>Surgery (arthroscopic subacromial decompression):</strong> Not recommended as routine (CSAW 2018); consider in refractory cases after 6+ months of structured physiotherapy</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<p>Generally good with structured physiotherapy:</p><ul><li>40–80% of patients resolve within 12 months with physiotherapy</li><li>CSAW trial: all three groups (physio, decompression, sham) improved significantly — reinforces physiotherapy as definitive treatment</li><li>Negative prognostic factors: psychological distress, catastrophising, high baseline pain, work-related aetiology</li><li>Recurrence rate 25–40% without addressing underlying biomechanical factors</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>CSAW Trial (Beard et al., 2018, NEJM):</strong> No significant difference between physiotherapy, arthroscopic decompression, and sham surgery. N=313. Landmark trial.</li><li><strong>NICE NG248 (2023):</strong> Physiotherapy as first-line; corticosteroid injection as adjunct for short-term pain; surgery only in refractory cases after structured physiotherapy</li><li><strong>Cochrane Review (Hanratty et al., 2012):</strong> Moderate evidence for exercise over no treatment; manual therapy as adjunct adds benefit</li><li><strong>Boyles et al. (2009):</strong> Thoracic manipulation significantly improves shoulder pain and function in SIS</li><li><strong>Lombardi et al. (2008):</strong> Progressive exercise programme superior to corticosteroid injection at 8 months</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'adhesive-capsulitis',
    name: 'Adhesive Capsulitis (Frozen Shoulder)',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Adhesive capsulitis (frozen shoulder)</strong> is a condition characterised by a progressive, painful restriction of active and passive glenohumeral movement in all planes, secondary to diffuse capsular inflammation and fibrosis. Prevalence is 2–5% of the general population, peaking at 40–60 years. Idiopathic (primary) in most cases; secondary adhesive capsulitis follows shoulder injury, surgery, or systemic conditions.</p><p><strong>Three clinical stages (Reeves, 1975 / Hannafin & Chiaia, 2000):</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Stage 1 — Painful ('Freezing'):</strong> 2–9 months. Diffuse shoulder pain with minimal restriction. Histology: synovitis.</li><li><strong>Stage 2 — Frozen ('Stiffness'):</strong> 4–12 months. Reduced pain but progressive ROM loss. Histology: capsular fibrosis.</li><li><strong>Stage 3 — Thawing:</strong> 5–24 months. Gradual spontaneous recovery. ROM returns.</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p>The glenohumeral joint has the largest capsule of any joint in the body, with redundant inferior folds (axillary pouch) allowing full elevation. In adhesive capsulitis:</p><ul><li>Axillary recess obliteration is pathognomonic — normal joint volume 28 mL reduces to &lt;5 mL</li><li>Coracohumeral ligament thickening (from 1.9 mm to 3.9 mm — Lo et al.) at rotator interval</li><li>Posterior capsule tightening contributes to IR restriction</li><li>Rotator interval involvement (between supraspinatus and subscapularis tendons) is the most consistent pathological site</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p>The dominant model involves an inflammatory-fibroproliferative cascade:</p><ul><li>Synovitis with CD4+ T-cell infiltration and elevated IL-1, IL-6, TNF-α</li><li>Fibroblast proliferation and transformation to myofibroblasts</li><li>Type III collagen deposition → type I remodelling → capsular contracture</li><li>Neurofibroblastic tissue in rotator interval (similar to Dupuytren's fibroblasts)</li></ul><p>The condition is fundamentally a fibrotic process, not simply inflammation. TGF-β1 drives the fibrotic cascade. This explains why anti-inflammatory treatments have limited long-term effect and why the fibrotic stage is more resistant to treatment.</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Prolonged arm immobilisation post-injury/surgery</li><li>Poorly managed rotator cuff pathology</li><li>Stroke with affected shoulder immobility</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Diabetes mellitus (10× increased risk; bilateral in 50% of diabetics)</li><li>Female sex (70% of primary cases)</li><li>Age 40–60 years</li><li>Thyroid disease (hypo- and hyperthyroid)</li><li>Dupuytren's contracture (same fibroblastic aetiology)</li><li>Cardiac disease and cardiac surgery</li><li>Non-dominant arm (idiopathic primary)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Diffuse, aching shoulder pain (often worse at night, lying on affected side), progressive loss of shoulder movement in ALL planes, difficulty reaching overhead, behind back, and out to side.</p><p><strong>Key diagnostic finding:</strong> Restricted <em>passive</em> ROM in a capsular pattern — ER most restricted, then abduction, then IR. This distinguishes it from rotator cuff pathology (where active is more limited than passive).</p><p><strong>Typical ROM findings:</strong> ER &lt;30°, abduction &lt;90°, IR &lt;L1 vertebra. In-plane end-feel is hard/springy rather than tissue stretch.</p><p><strong>Hallmark:</strong> Absence of glenohumeral movement on palpation during shoulder abduction (scapular substitution only).</p>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>DASH</strong> — MCID 10–15 points; functional upper limb measure</li><li><strong>Oxford Shoulder Score</strong> — MCID 8 points</li><li><strong>SPADI (Shoulder Pain and Disability Index)</strong> — MCID 8–13 points; sensitive for frozen shoulder</li><li><strong>ROM measurement:</strong> Goniometry — ER at side (most sensitive), abduction, and IR (vertebral level)</li><li><strong>PSFS</strong> — patient-specific activity monitoring</li><li><strong>Sleep disturbance VAS</strong> — important quality of life marker in freezing phase</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>X-ray:</strong> Usually normal. Rules out OA, calcification, trauma. Peri-articular osteopenia may be present.</li><li><strong>USS:</strong> Coracohumeral ligament thickening (&gt;3 mm = 96% sensitivity for adhesive capsulitis); hyperaemia at rotator interval on Doppler</li><li><strong>MRI arthrogram:</strong> Gold standard — demonstrates obliterated axillary recess, reduced joint volume. Non-contrast MRI: capsular thickening and signal change at rotator interval.</li><li><strong>Arthrogram (plain):</strong> Reduced joint volume (&lt;10 mL with pain on injection = diagnostic)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Glenohumeral osteoarthritis (XR shows joint space narrowing)</li><li>Rotator cuff tear (ROM relatively preserved passively; USS/MRI distinguishes)</li><li>Subacromial impingement (no passive ROM restriction)</li><li>Cervical radiculopathy (dermatomal pain pattern, cervical provocation positive)</li><li>Malignancy (constant pain, night sweats, weight loss)</li><li>Post-traumatic stiffness (clear history of injury/fracture/surgery)</li><li>Inflammatory arthritis (RA, seronegative)</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Unremitting constant pain unresponsive to any position — malignancy/infection must be excluded</li><li>Fever with shoulder pain and restriction — septic arthritis (surgical emergency)</li><li>Rapid progressive stiffness &lt;4 weeks — always image (malignancy, destructive arthropathy)</li><li>Age &lt;40 years with "frozen shoulder" — unusual; always investigate for other causes</li><li>Associated unexplained weight loss, night sweats — systemic malignancy</li><li>Bilateral simultaneous presentation in non-diabetic — consider systemic disease (PMR, inflammatory arthritis)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Stage 1 — Painful/Freezing Phase</div><ul><li><strong>Pain management priority:</strong> Avoid aggressive stretching (exacerbates inflammatory cascade); NSAIDs; corticosteroid injection (subacromial or intra-articular) — most effective in this stage</li><li>Pendulum exercises, pain-free active-assisted ROM</li><li>Perineural nerve treatment if neuropathic component</li><li>Patient education: natural history (recovery in 1–3 years), validate experience, goal-setting</li><li>Shoulder blade setting, gentle rhythmic stabilisations</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Stage 2 — Frozen/Stiffness Phase</div><ul><li><strong>Progressive mobilisation:</strong> End-range passive stretching (tolerated; Diercks & Stevens, 2004 showed gentle &gt; aggressive)</li><li>Glenohumeral mobilisations (Maitland Grade III–IV): inferior, posterior, and anterior glides</li><li>Capsular stretching: posterior capsule (sleeper stretch), ER stretching (doorframe stretch)</li><li>PNF techniques: hold-relax for ER and abduction</li><li><strong>Hydrodilatation (distension arthroplasty):</strong> Injection of saline + steroid under fluoroscopy — disrupts capsular adhesions; NICE-approved; Rowe & Khaled (2021) Cochrane: short-term benefit over physiotherapy alone</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Stage 3 — Thawing Phase</div><ul><li>Progressive ROM exercises: Codman circles, wand exercises, pulley systems</li><li>Strengthening: rotator cuff and scapular stabilisers as ROM returns</li><li>Functional rehabilitation: ADL-specific tasks, overhead activities</li><li><strong>Manipulation Under Anaesthesia (MUA) / Arthroscopic capsular release:</strong> For refractory cases &gt;12–18 months; arthroplasty technique superior to MUA (controlled tissue release)</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<p>Complete spontaneous recovery in majority of patients (80–90%) but timeline is prolonged:</p><ul><li>Mean duration: 18–30 months</li><li>~10–20% have persistent mild restriction at 5 years</li><li>Diabetic patients: longer duration, higher recurrence, bilateral involvement common</li><li>Corticosteroid injection reduces pain in short term (0–6 weeks) but does not alter natural history (Carette et al., 2003, NEJM)</li><li>Hydrodilatation: superior to physiotherapy alone for short-term pain/function (Cochrane, 2021)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Carette et al. (2003, NEJM):</strong> Corticosteroid injection + physio = physio alone at 6 months; injection provides short-term (4–6 week) pain benefit</li><li><strong>Diercks & Stevens (2004, JSE):</strong> Gentle supervised physiotherapy superior to aggressive supervised physiotherapy — supports avoiding aggressive stretching in painful phase</li><li><strong>Cochrane Review (Rowe & Khaled, 2021):</strong> Hydrodilatation provides short-term benefit over placebo; evidence modest quality</li><li><strong>NICE NG248 (2023):</strong> Physiotherapy, corticosteroid injection, and hydrodilatation all recommended; surgery for refractory cases</li><li><strong>Blomqvist et al. (2019, BJSM):</strong> Systematic review — corticosteroid injection superior to placebo for short-term pain; equivalent to physiotherapy at 6 months</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'glenohumeral-instability',
    name: 'Glenohumeral Instability',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Glenohumeral instability</strong> refers to symptomatic translation of the humeral head relative to the glenoid, encompassing a spectrum from subtle microinstability to frank dislocation. Classification:</p><ul><li><strong>Direction:</strong> Anterior (most common, 95%), posterior, multidirectional (MDI)</li><li><strong>Aetiology:</strong> Traumatic (TUBS: Traumatic, Unilateral, Bankart lesion, Surgery) vs Atraumatic (AMBRI: Atraumatic, Multidirectional, Bilateral, Rehabilitation, Inferior capsule)</li><li><strong>Degree:</strong> Dislocation (complete), subluxation (partial), microinstability</li></ul><p>Anterior dislocation prevalence: 11.2 per 100,000/year. Peak incidence young males (16–20 years) in collision sports. Recurrence rate: 80–90% in patients &lt;20 years without surgical stabilisation.</p>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p><strong>Static stabilisers:</strong></p><ul><li>Glenoid labrum (deepens glenoid from 5 mm to 9 mm)</li><li>Glenohumeral ligaments: SGHL (superior — limits inferior translation, ER), MGHL (middle), IGHL (inferior — primary anterior restraint at 90° abduction; anterior band limits anterior translation)</li><li>Coracohumeral ligament</li><li>Glenoid shape/version</li></ul><p><strong>Dynamic stabilisers:</strong></p><ul><li>Rotator cuff (concavity-compression mechanism)</li><li>Long head biceps (superior stabiliser)</li><li>Deltoid, periscapular muscles</li></ul><p><strong>Bankart lesion:</strong> Avulsion of anteroinferior labrum ± periosteum (labral tear). <strong>Bony Bankart:</strong> fracture of anterior glenoid rim. <strong>Hill-Sachs:</strong> posterolateral humeral head impaction fracture from anterior dislocation. Engaging Hill-Sachs lesions significantly increase recurrence risk.</p>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p><strong>Traumatic anterior instability:</strong> Forced abduction + ER (e.g., arm tackle, fall) overloads IGHL anterior band → Bankart lesion (anterior labral avulsion) in 85–90% of first dislocations. Repeated dislocations cause: progressive glenoid bone loss, Hill-Sachs enlargement, IGHL laxity, rotator cuff dysfunction.</p><p><strong>Posterior instability:</strong> Less common. Fall on outstretched arm in flexion/IR, or repetitive posterior loading (offensive linemen, press-type exercises). Posterior Bankart/posterior capsular laxity. Associated with reverse Hill-Sachs (McLaughlin lesion).</p><p><strong>MDI:</strong> Generalised ligamentous laxity (Beighton score), collagen abnormality, repetitive microtrauma overhead. Bilateral sulcus sign pathognomonic. Responds best to rehabilitation.</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Participation in collision/overhead sports</li><li>Poor neuromuscular control / rotator cuff weakness</li><li>Previous ipsilateral dislocation</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Age &lt;25 years (recurrence up to 90%)</li><li>Male sex</li><li>Glenoid hypoplasia or excessive retroversion</li><li>Hypermobility/connective tissue disorders (Ehlers-Danlos, Marfan's)</li><li>Bony Bankart lesion &gt;25% glenoid surface area</li><li>Engaging Hill-Sachs lesion</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Post-dislocation:</strong> Pain, arm held in slight abduction/ER, squared-off appearance (loss of deltoid round), prominent acromion, loss of deltoid fullness anteriorly.</p><p><strong>Chronic instability:</strong> Apprehension with arm in provocative position (abduction/ER for anterior; forward flexion/IR for posterior), sense of "slipping out," functional limitation in overhead activities.</p><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th></tr><tr><td>Apprehension Test (anterior)</td><td>72%</td><td>96%</td></tr><tr><td>Relocation Test (Jobe)</td><td>81%</td><td>92%</td></tr><tr><td>Anterior Release Test</td><td>92%</td><td>89%</td></tr><tr><td>Load and Shift Test</td><td>50%</td><td>100% (grade III)</td></tr><tr><td>Sulcus Sign (&gt;1 cm = MDI)</td><td>28%</td><td>97%</td></tr><tr><td>Gagey Hyperabduction Test (MDI)</td><td>—</td><td>high specificity</td></tr></table>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>WOSI (Western Ontario Shoulder Instability Index)</strong> — 21-item; most responsive disease-specific PRO for instability; MCID 10.4%; gold standard for instability research</li><li><strong>ASES</strong> — MCID 12–17 points</li><li><strong>Melbourne Instability Shoulder Scale (MISS)</strong></li><li><strong>Rowe Score</strong> — includes recurrence, function, motion; widely used in surgical literature</li><li><strong>Beighton Hypermobility Score</strong> — assess generalised laxity (/9; ≥4/9 = hypermobility)</li><li><strong>Functional Assessment:</strong> Kinematic shoulder screen, rotator cuff strength (ER:IR ratio), proprioceptive testing</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>X-ray:</strong> AP, Y-scapular, and axillary views. Identify Hill-Sachs (AP IR), Bankart (axillary), glenoid erosion, dislocation direction confirmation.</li><li><strong>CT ± 3D reconstruction:</strong> Gold standard for glenoid bone loss quantification (critical threshold: 25% of glenoid). En face view (true AP glenoid) for "glenoid track" analysis with Hill-Sachs.</li><li><strong>MRI arthrogram:</strong> Labral tears (Bankart, posterior Bankart, ALPSA, HAGL lesions), capsular integrity, rotator cuff.</li><li><strong>USS:</strong> Limited for labral assessment; can evaluate rotator cuff and anterior structures.</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Rotator cuff tear</li><li>SLAP lesion</li><li>AC joint injury</li><li>Brachial plexus injury (post-dislocation axillary nerve palsy in 5–30%)</li><li>Proximal humerus fracture</li><li>Biceps tendon rupture</li><li>Cervical radiculopathy</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Suspected concurrent axillary nerve injury (deltoid weakness, patch of numbness badge area, post-dislocation) — arrange urgent neurology/orthopaedic review</li><li>Suspected vascular injury: expanding haematoma, absent radial pulse, distal limb pallor/ischaemia — vascular surgery emergency</li><li>Fracture-dislocation: prominent deformity, unable to relocate — urgent orthopaedic reduction</li><li>Open dislocation — surgical emergency</li><li>Recurrent episodes increasing in frequency with minor mechanism — bony Bankart/engaging Hill-Sachs: orthopaedic surgical assessment essential</li><li>Young patient (&lt;25 years) first dislocation: counsel regarding 70–90% recurrence without surgery</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Post-Dislocation Acute Phase (0–3 weeks)</div><ul><li>Reduction confirmation (post-reduction X-ray), NV status documentation</li><li>Sling immobilisation: 3 weeks (evidence for ER position brace reducing recurrence in young males — Itoi et al.)</li><li>Ice, analgesia</li><li>Early pendulum exercises, wrist/elbow active ROM</li><li>Axillary nerve check: deltoid contraction, lateral shoulder sensation</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Rehabilitation Phase (3–12 weeks)</div><ul><li>Progressive rotator cuff activation: IR, ER (avoid provocative positions initially)</li><li>Scapular stabilisation: lower trapezius, serratus anterior</li><li>Dynamic stabilisation: perturbation training, PNF patterns</li><li>Proprioceptive retraining: closed chain exercises, ball-on-wall circles</li><li>Posterior capsule flexibility if restricted</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Return to Sport (3–6+ months)</div><ul><li>MDI: Tobias/Rockwood rehabilitation programme — 6–12 months; 80% success without surgery</li><li>Traumatic instability (&lt;25 years): refer for surgical stabilisation discussion — Latarjet/Bankart repair reduces recurrence to &lt;10%</li><li>Return to contact sport: full ROM, symmetrical strength, apprehension test negative, sport-specific clearance</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Young males &lt;20 years: 80–90% recurrence without surgery</li><li>Adults &gt;40 years: lower recurrence but higher associated rotator cuff tear rate</li><li>Arthroscopic Bankart: recurrence 5–20%; superior to open for soft tissue lesions</li><li>Latarjet procedure: recurrence &lt;5%; preferred when bony glenoid loss &gt;20–25%</li><li>MDI: 85–90% respond to rehabilitation alone (Burkhead & Rockwood programme)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Itoi et al. (2003):</strong> ER immobilisation reduces recurrence vs IR sling in young males</li><li><strong>Bottoni et al. (2002, AJSM):</strong> Arthroscopic stabilisation superior to immobilisation for first-time traumatic dislocation in young military personnel</li><li><strong>Burkhead & Rockwood (1992):</strong> Landmark physiotherapy programme for MDI — 85% success with structured rehabilitation</li><li><strong>Laterjet vs Bankart (Mizuno et al., 2014):</strong> Superior outcomes with Latarjet when glenoid bone loss &gt;25%</li><li><strong>NICE NG248 (2023):</strong> Physiotherapy for atraumatic instability; surgical referral for traumatic recurrent instability</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'slap-lesion',
    name: 'SLAP Lesion',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p>A <strong>SLAP (Superior Labrum Anterior to Posterior) lesion</strong> is a tear of the superior glenoid labrum, involving the biceps anchor (long head biceps tendon origin), extending anteriorly and posteriorly. Snyder et al. (1990) originally described four types; now expanded to 10+ types. Most clinically significant: Type II (detachment of labrum from glenoid — most common, ~55%) and Type IV (bucket-handle tear extending into biceps tendon).</p><p>Prevalence in shoulder arthroscopy: 6–11%. Common in overhead throwing athletes (pitchers, swimmers, tennis players) and middle-aged patients following traction injury. Often coexists with rotator cuff pathology in older patients.</p>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p>The glenoid labrum is a fibrocartilaginous ring deepening the shallow glenoid fossa. Superiorly, it blends with the long head of biceps tendon origin (LHBT), which attaches predominantly to the posterior-superior labrum (54%) and secondarily to the supraglenoid tubercle (37%). The LHBT anchor acts as a "peel-back" mechanism — in abduction/ER, the posterior LHBT rotates and twists, peeling the labral anchor off the glenoid.</p><p>Key anatomical variants: cord-like MGHL (Buford complex) and sublabral foramen may mimic SLAP — important to distinguish on MRI.</p>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p>Two primary mechanisms:</p><ul><li><strong>Repetitive traction/peel-back:</strong> Overhead throwing — during late cocking (maximum ER, 90° abduction), LHBT rotates and twists superiorly; with arm acceleration the tensile load is transmitted to the labral anchor. Over thousands of throws, cumulative fatigue failure of the labral-glenoid junction.</li><li><strong>Acute compression-traction:</strong> FOOSH (fall on outstretched hand) — compressive load; acute distraction (catching heavy object, shoulder dislocation).</li></ul><p>Type II SLAP: superior labrum detaches from glenoid rim, altering biceps anchor stability and glenohumeral kinematics. This increases glenohumeral translation and alters joint compression, causing pain and functional limitation.</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>High overhead throwing volume</li><li>GIRD (Glenohumeral Internal Rotation Deficit &gt;15°)</li><li>Poor posterior capsule flexibility</li><li>Scapular dyskinesis</li><li>Technique errors in throwing mechanics</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Participation in overhead sport (pitching, swimming, tennis, volleyball)</li><li>Age — different mechanisms: acute traction in young athletes; degenerative in >40 years</li><li>Glenohumeral instability</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Deep posterior shoulder pain/ache, exacerbated by overhead activity, often at late-cocking phase. Clicking, clunking, or popping with shoulder movement. Pain with pushing off armrests, reaching overhead. Night pain is variable.</p><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th></tr><tr><td>O'Brien's (Active Compression)</td><td>47%</td><td>55%</td></tr><tr><td>Crank Test</td><td>72%</td><td>98%</td></tr><tr><td>Anterior Slide Test</td><td>78%</td><td>91%</td></tr><tr><td>Speed's Test</td><td>32%</td><td>75%</td></tr><tr><td>Biceps Load II</td><td>90%</td><td>97%</td></tr><tr><td>Kim's Test (combined)</td><td>74%</td><td>94%</td></tr></table><p><em>Note: No single test is diagnostic. Combination of positive O'Brien + Crank improves diagnostic accuracy. MRI arthrogram remains the reference standard.</em></p>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>WOSI</strong> — best for overhead athlete instability/SLAP</li><li><strong>ASES</strong> — MCID 12–17 points</li><li><strong>DASH</strong> — MCID 10–15 points</li><li><strong>GIRD assessment:</strong> Supine IR at 90° abduction using inclinometer; &gt;15° side-to-side difference = clinically significant GIRD</li><li><strong>Throwing assessment:</strong> Video analysis of throwing mechanics (late cocking position, trunk rotation, scapular position)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>MRI arthrogram (gadolinium):</strong> Gold standard. Contrast enters the tear, outlining labral detachment. Sensitivity 82%, specificity 98% for Type II SLAP. Non-contrast MRI sensitivity only 55%.</li><li><strong>Diagnostic arthroscopy:</strong> Definitive — assess labral attachment stability by "peel-back" test under anaesthesia (positive if labrum peels posteriorly with arm in abduction/ER)</li><li><strong>USS:</strong> Limited role for labral pathology; primarily used for rotator cuff assessment</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Biceps tendinopathy (LHBT)</li><li>Subacromial impingement</li><li>Rotator cuff tear</li><li>Glenohumeral instability</li><li>Internal impingement (posterior superior labrum, supraspinatus articular surface)</li><li>AC joint pathology</li><li>Cervical radiculopathy</li><li>Normal anatomical variants (sublabral foramen, Buford complex)</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Acute locked shoulder post-trauma (displaced bucket-handle tear locking joint) — urgent orthopaedic referral</li><li>Progressive neurological deficit in throwing athlete — consider thoracic outlet syndrome or suprascapular nerve entrapment</li><li>Suprascapular nerve palsy (paralabral cyst compressing suprascapular notch): confirm with MRI, EMG</li><li>Cervical myelopathy with upper limb symptoms — see cervical myelopathy pathway</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Conservative Management (Initial 3 months)</div><ul><li>Activity modification: reduce overhead throwing volume; avoid provocative positions</li><li>Posterior capsule stretching: sleeper stretch, cross-body adduction stretch (address GIRD — target &lt;15° asymmetry)</li><li>Rotator cuff strengthening: ER emphasis, internal/external rotation at 90° abduction</li><li>Scapular stabilisation: lower trapezius (prone Y), serratus anterior</li><li>Biceps loading: eccentric curls, reverse wrist curls</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Rehabilitation Phase (3–6 months)</div><ul><li>Interval throwing programme (once asymptomatic)</li><li>Progressive overhead loading: begin at 50% effort, distance, advance weekly</li><li>Core and hip strengthening (kinetic chain for throwers)</li><li>Throwing mechanics correction with video analysis</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Surgical Decision</div><ul><li>Type II SLAP in young overhead athlete: arthroscopic repair if failed 3 months conservative (suture anchor re-attachment)</li><li>&gt;40 years: biceps tenodesis superior to SLAP repair (Denard et al.) — preserves biceps function with better outcomes in older patients</li><li>Post-operative return to pitching: 12 months; competitive pitch: 9–12 months</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Conservative management: 40–60% success in non-throwing athletes; poor in overhead throwers</li><li>Arthroscopic SLAP repair (Type II): 85–94% good/excellent results; return to previous level of sport 63–73% in throwers</li><li>Biceps tenodesis in patients &gt;40 years: equivalent or superior to SLAP repair at &gt;2 years follow-up</li><li>Revision surgery: poor outcomes; best avoided</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Snyder et al. (1990):</strong> Original SLAP classification (Types I–IV)</li><li><strong>Denard et al. (2012):</strong> Biceps tenodesis superior to SLAP repair in patients &gt;36 years</li><li><strong>Alpert et al. (2010):</strong> Posterior capsular stretching reduces GIRD significantly — key non-operative intervention</li><li><strong>ESSKA consensus (2018):</strong> Conservative management as first-line for 3 months; surgical decision based on age, activity level, and coexisting pathology</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'acromioclavicular-joint-injury',
    name: 'Acromioclavicular Joint Injury',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p>An <strong>acromioclavicular (AC) joint injury</strong> is a disruption of the acromioclavicular and/or coracoclavicular ligaments, typically caused by a direct fall on the point of the shoulder with the arm adducted. Classified using the <strong>Rockwood classification (Types I–VI):</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Type I:</strong> AC ligament sprain only; joint intact</li><li><strong>Type II:</strong> AC ligament rupture; CC ligament sprain; &lt;25% clavicle displacement</li><li><strong>Type III:</strong> AC + CC ligament rupture; 25–100% displacement; clinically controversial surgical vs conservative management</li><li><strong>Type IV:</strong> Posterior clavicle displacement (buttonhole through trapezius)</li><li><strong>Type V:</strong> 100–300% displacement; gross deformity</li><li><strong>Type VI:</strong> Inferior displacement (rare; below coracoid)</li></ul><p>Types I–II: managed conservatively. Types IV–VI: surgical. Type III: debated.</p>` },
      { title: 'Anatomy', open: false, content: `<p>The AC joint is a plane synovial joint with an intra-articular disc (degenerates by 4th decade). Stabilised by:</p><ul><li><strong>AC ligaments:</strong> Superior (strongest), inferior, anterior, and posterior — primary horizontal stabilisers</li><li><strong>Coracoclavicular ligaments:</strong> Conoid (medial, vertical restraint) and trapezoid (lateral, horizontal restraint) — primary vertical stabilisers</li><li><strong>Deltoid and trapezius muscular attachments</strong></li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Contact/collision sport participation</li><li>Cycling (falls)</li><li>Inadequate protective equipment</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Male sex (7:1 ratio)</li><li>Age 20–30 years (peak)</li><li>Specific sport participation (rugby, cycling, skiing)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Localised AC joint tenderness, pain on cross-body adduction, pain on overhead activities. Visible step deformity (Types III–V). Ability to reduce deformity by pushing up on the elbow.</p><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th></tr><tr><td>Horizontal Adduction Test</td><td>77%</td><td>79%</td></tr><tr><td>AC Joint Palpation</td><td>96%</td><td>10%</td></tr><tr><td>O'Brien's Test</td><td>41%</td><td>95% (AC specific)</td></tr><tr><td>AC Joint Injection Test</td><td>85–90%</td><td>high</td></tr></table>` },
      { title: 'Assessment & Outcome Measures', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>ACROMIOCLAVICULAR JOINT INSTABILITY (ACJI) Score</strong></li><li><strong>DASH</strong> — MCID 10–15 points</li><li><strong>Oxford Shoulder Score</strong></li><li><strong>Radiographic grading:</strong> Weighted stress views (10 lb weight) for Type II vs III distinction (CC interval: normal &lt;13 mm; &gt;25% asymmetry = significant)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Investigations & Imaging', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>X-ray:</strong> Bilateral weight-bearing AP (with 10 lb weights) and Zanca view (upward tilt 10–15°). Measure CC interval and AC joint width.</li><li><strong>MRI:</strong> Assess ligament integrity, intra-articular disc, associated rotator cuff/biceps pathology</li><li><strong>USS:</strong> Dynamic stress assessment of AC joint</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Differential Diagnosis', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Distal clavicle osteolysis</li><li>AC joint osteoarthritis</li><li>Sternoclavicular joint injury</li><li>Clavicle fracture</li><li>Rotator cuff pathology</li></ul>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Type IV–VI injury — prompt orthopaedic surgical referral</li><li>Associated clavicle fracture — full-length clavicle X-ray</li><li>Neurovascular compromise (brachial plexus traction, subclavian vessel injury in high-energy Type VI)</li><li>Open injury</li><li>Posterior displacement (Type IV) — may tent skin or compress neurovascular structures</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute (0–2 weeks) — Types I & II</div><ul><li>Sling for comfort (3–5 days); avoid prolonged immobilisation</li><li>Ice, NSAIDs for pain management</li><li>Pendulum exercises from day 2</li><li>Avoid provocative movements (cross-body, overhead)</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute (2–6 weeks)</div><ul><li>Progressive ROM: active-assisted → active; full elevation by 3–4 weeks (Types I/II)</li><li>Rotator cuff and scapular stabiliser strengthening</li><li>Avoid horizontal adduction and heavy overhead loading until 6 weeks</li><li>Type III: conservative management 3 months before surgical decision</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Return to Sport (6–12 weeks Types I/II; 3–6 months Type III)</div><ul><li>Full strength and ROM restoration</li><li>Contact sport return: protective padding (donut pad) over AC joint</li><li>Post-surgical (Hook plate / Tightrope / reconstruction): structured 3–6 month rehabilitation programme</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Prognosis & Outcomes', open: false, content: `<ul><li>Type I: Full recovery 2–4 weeks; rare long-term sequelae</li><li>Type II: Full recovery 4–8 weeks; 25% develop AC OA long-term; 10% chronic pain</li><li>Type III: Conservative management yields 80% good results; surgery not proven superior in multiple RCTs (Ceccarelli et al., 2008)</li><li>Types IV–VI post-surgery: Good/excellent outcomes in 80–90%</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Ceccarelli et al. (2008, JSE):</strong> RCT — Type III AC injury: no significant difference conservative vs surgical at 6 years</li><li><strong>Rockwood classification (1984):</strong> Standard classification system used globally</li><li><strong>ISAKOS consensus (2021):</strong> Conservative management for Types I–II; individualised approach for Type III based on activity level and deformity</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'biceps-tendinopathy',
    name: 'Biceps Tendinopathy',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Biceps tendinopathy</strong> most commonly refers to pathology of the <strong>long head of biceps brachii tendon (LHBT)</strong> within the bicipital groove and intertubercular sulcus. It accounts for approximately 5% of isolated shoulder pain presentations, but coexists with rotator cuff pathology in up to 95% of cases. The LHBT is 9 cm in length and travels in the bicipital groove (covered by the transverse humeral ligament) before entering the glenohumeral joint.</p><p>Types: <em>Primary</em> (isolated LHBT tendinopathy — uncommon), <em>Secondary</em> (associated with rotator cuff pathology — most common), and <em>instability</em> (medial subluxation from groove due to subscapularis tear).</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Overhead throwing sports</li><li>Repetitive lifting with elbow flexion</li><li>Associated rotator cuff pathology (proximate predisposing factor)</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Age (degenerative changes &gt;40 years)</li><li>Bicipital groove morphology (narrow groove, medial wall angle)</li><li>Inflammatory arthropathy</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Anterior shoulder pain in the bicipital groove, radiating to the anterior arm. Pain with flexion, supination, and overhead activities. Night pain is variable.</p><h4>Special Tests</h4><table><tr><th>Test</th><th>Sensitivity</th><th>Specificity</th></tr><tr><td>Speed's Test</td><td>32%</td><td>75%</td></tr><tr><td>Yergason's Test</td><td>43%</td><td>79%</td></tr><tr><td>Bicipital Groove Palpation</td><td>53%</td><td>54%</td></tr><tr><td>Biceps Load II</td><td>90%</td><td>97% (for SLAP)</td></tr></table><p><em>Note: Tests for LHBT have generally poor sensitivity in isolation; must correlate with imaging.</em></p>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Sudden "pop" + painful bulge in anterior arm = acute LHBT rupture ("Popeye deformity") — orthopaedic assessment for tenodesis (active population) vs conservative (elderly)</li><li>Medial subluxation of biceps tendon from groove = associated subscapularis tear — urgent USS/MRI</li><li>Rapid progression with constitutional symptoms — malignancy</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute Phase</div><ul><li>Load management: avoid provocative elbow flexion/supination under load</li><li>Isometric biceps holds (3×45s) for pain modulation</li><li>Address coexisting rotator cuff pathology</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute & Chronic</div><ul><li>Eccentric-concentric loading programme (3×12 slow curls with controlled lowering)</li><li>Rotator cuff strengthening (co-stabiliser)</li><li>Scapular stabilisation</li><li>Corticosteroid injection to sheath (short-term relief; limit ≤2 injections — rupture risk)</li><li>Biceps tenodesis: surgical option for persistent pain with confirmed LHBT pathology, especially if combined subscapularis tear</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Hitchcock & Bechtol (1948):</strong> Original description of bicipital tendinitis and groove anatomy</li><li><strong>Ahrens & Ghosh (2004):</strong> USS-guided injection superior to blind injection for LHBT sheath</li><li><strong>NICE NG248 (2023):</strong> Conservative management first-line; consider tenodesis for failed conservative treatment with confirmed structural pathology</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'calcific-tendinitis',
    name: 'Calcific Tendinitis',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Calcific tendinitis of the shoulder</strong> is characterised by calcium hydroxyapatite crystal deposition within the rotator cuff tendon, most commonly the supraspinatus (80%). It affects 2–8% of the population, with peak incidence 30–60 years. Most cases are self-limiting, though acute episodes can be exquisitely painful.</p><p><strong>Gärtner classification (morphology):</strong></p><ul><li>Type A: Dense, homogeneous, well-demarcated (harder calcification, more painful)</li><li>Type B: Dense, heterogeneous, well-demarcated</li><li>Type C: Inhomogeneous, ill-defined (softer, resorptive phase)</li><li>Type D: Dystrophic (at tendon insertion, different mechanism)</li></ul><p>French & Gärtner (1999) — Type C calcifications respond best to needling. Evolution: formative → resting → resorptive → post-calcific.</p>` },
      { title: 'Pathophysiology', open: false, content: `<p>Uhlin's theory: local hypoxia in the critical zone triggers fibrocartilaginous transformation of tenocytes → calcium crystal deposition (formative phase). During the resorptive phase, phagocytes invade — this generates intense local pressure and acute, excruciating pain. Spontaneous rupture into the subacromial bursa commonly terminates the acute episode.</p>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Acute:</strong> Sudden-onset, excruciating shoulder pain (7–10/10), preventing any shoulder movement, often beginning at night. Patient typically holds arm in adduction with marked guarding.</p><p><strong>Chronic:</strong> Intermittent shoulder aching, similar to rotator cuff tendinopathy but punctuated by acute exacerbations.</p><p>Painful arc present; restricted ROM during acute episode. Supraspinatus tenderness.</p>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Acute presentation with fever — rule out septic arthritis / acute crystal arthropathy (gout/pseudogout)</li><li>Bilateral presentation — consider systemic crystal arthropathy (CPPD, hydroxyapatite deposition disease)</li><li>No radiological calcification on X-ray despite acute presentation — confirm diagnosis</li><li>Calcification plus severe bone destruction — consider malignancy or infection</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute Exacerbation</div><ul><li>Rest, ice, NSAIDs (ibuprofen 400 mg TDS × 5–7 days)</li><li>Corticosteroid injection: subacromial — rapid pain relief (1–3 days); does not dissolve calcium but reduces bursal inflammation</li><li>Avoid aggressive physiotherapy during acute phase</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute / Chronic</div><ul><li>Progressive rotator cuff and scapular loading (as per tendinopathy protocol)</li><li><strong>Ultrasound-guided needling (barbotage):</strong> Lavage and aspiration of calcium deposit — most effective for Type C (soft) calcifications; Cochrane (de Witte et al., 2012) — moderate evidence for pain reduction</li><li><strong>Extracorporeal Shockwave Therapy (ESWT):</strong> NICE-approved; moderate quality evidence for calcific tendinitis; dissolves calcium crystals; 3–6 sessions; Gerdesmeyer et al. (2003, JBJS) — high-energy ESWT superior to sham</li><li>Radial ESWT: lower energy, less evidence but widely available</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>Gerdesmeyer et al. (2003, JBJS):</strong> RCT — high-energy ESWT significantly superior to sham for calcific tendinitis at 6 months</li><li><strong>NICE IPG499 (2014):</strong> ESWT for calcific tendinitis — evidence adequate for use with normal consent</li><li><strong>Cochrane (de Witte et al., 2012):</strong> USS-guided needling reduces pain moderately; lack of high-quality RCTs</li><li><strong>Gärtner & Heyer (1995):</strong> Classification system and natural history of calcific tendinitis</li></ul>` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 'shoulder-osteoarthritis',
    name: 'Shoulder Osteoarthritis',
    category: 'MSK',
    subcategory: 'Shoulder',
    sections: [
      { title: 'Overview & Definition', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Glenohumeral osteoarthritis (GH OA)</strong> is degenerative joint disease characterised by progressive cartilage loss, subchondral bone changes, osteophyte formation, and synovial inflammation of the glenohumeral joint. It is significantly less common than hip or knee OA (prevalence 15–20% in adults &gt;65 years radiographically), as the shoulder is non-weight-bearing. It accounts for 25,000 shoulder arthroplasties in the UK annually.</p><p>Types: Primary (idiopathic), Secondary (post-traumatic, post-inflammatory, post-avascular necrosis, post-rotator cuff arthropathy).</p>` },
      { title: 'Risk Factors', open: true, content: `<h4>Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Occupational heavy manual labour</li><li>Post-traumatic joint incongruity</li><li>Repeated corticosteroid injection</li></ul><h4>Non-Modifiable</h4><ul><li>Age (strongest predictor)</li><li>Previous shoulder injury/surgery</li><li>Rotator cuff tear arthropathy (Hamada classification)</li><li>Inflammatory arthritis (RA, AS)</li><li>Avascular necrosis</li><li>Chondrolysis (post-laser, thermal)</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Clinical Presentation', open: true, content: `<p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Deep, aching GH joint pain (anterior shoulder/deltoid), restricted movement (especially ER and cross-body adduction), crepitus, and stiffness (particularly morning stiffness &lt;30 min). Pain worse with activity.</p><p>Clinical: Restricted passive ROM in capsular pattern (ER &gt; abduction &gt; IR — different to adhesive capsulitis as crepitus present and hard end-feel). Glenoid facet tenderness (anterior). Axillary nerve deficit in advanced cases.</p>` },
      { title: '⚠ Red Flags', open: true, redFlag: true, content: `<ul><li>Rapid joint destruction in young patient — septic arthritis, avascular necrosis, malignancy</li><li>Bilateral symmetrical shoulder arthritis — inflammatory arthritis (RA, AS) requires rheumatology</li><li>Acute severe pain in established OA — consider pathological fracture or secondary infection</li><li>Constitutional symptoms — malignancy, infection</li></ul>` },
      { title: 'Physiotherapy Management', open: true, content: `<div class="phase-block phase-acute"><div class="phase-title">Acute / Pain-dominant</div><ul><li>Activity modification, joint protection education</li><li>Analgesics: paracetamol, NSAIDs (topical preferred in older patients — NICE)</li><li>Intra-articular corticosteroid injection (USS-guided preferred): short-term pain relief</li><li>Gentle ROM: pendulum, active-assisted exercises in pain-free range</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-subacute"><div class="phase-title">Sub-acute / Function</div><ul><li>ROM maintenance: capsular stretching, pulley exercises</li><li>Strengthening: rotator cuff and periscapular (avoid high-load exercises through restricted ROM)</li><li>Aquatic therapy: low-load environment for ROM and strength</li></ul></div><div class="phase-block phase-chronic"><div class="phase-title">Advanced / Pre/Post-surgical</div><ul><li>Shoulder arthroplasty discussion: Total shoulder arthroplasty (TSA) for primary GH OA; Reverse TSA (rTSA) for GH OA + rotator cuff arthropathy / cuff tear arthropathy</li><li>Pre-op prehabilitation: maximise ROM and strength</li><li>Post-op TSA: Phase 1 (0–6 weeks): pendulum, AAROM; Phase 2 (6–12 weeks): active ROM, isometrics; Phase 3 (3–6 months): strengthening; avoid &gt;90° elevation for 6 weeks</li></ul></div>` },
      { title: 'Evidence Base & Guidelines', open: false, content: `<ul><li><strong>NICE NG226 (OA, 2022):</strong> Exercise, weight management, and self-management first-line; topical NSAIDs preferred over oral in older adults; joint replacement for failed conservative management</li><li><strong>Cochrane (Mahomed et al., 2019):</strong> Total shoulder arthroplasty provides significant pain relief and functional improvement for GH OA</li><li><strong>Reverse TSA (Grammont, 1985):</strong> Revolutionised management of rotator cuff arthropathy — mediates CoR, improves deltoid function</li></ul>` }
    ]
  }
];
